Context¶

  • In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term.

  • The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human involvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

  • As a data scientist, you have to create an efficient model to classify these images into their respective categories.

Objective¶

  • Build a Convolutional Neural Network model which would classify the plant seedlings into their respective 12 categories.

Data Description¶

  • This dataset contains images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species. The data file names are: images.npy Label.csv

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

  • List of Plant species

1.Black-grass 2.Charlock 3.Cleavers 4.Common Chickweed 5.Common Wheat 6.Fat Hen 7.Loose Silky-bent 8.Maize 9.Scentless Mayweed 10.Shepherds Purse 11.Small-flowered Cranesbill 12.Sugar beet

Approach:¶

  • I have visualyzed the data, performed EDA. Applied one hot encoding, normalizing (to scale 0-1).
  • I've built 4 models - CNN, after applying data-augmentation on train data, without applying weights and Transfer learning (VGG).
  • For each model created model evaluation graph, confusion matrix and provided my insight.
  • I have not used google colab hence I did not use cv2_imshow (commented out). But after conversion to RGB from BGR, I visualized the image.
  • Finally I ended the project with my conclusions.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶¶

In [8]:
def plot_images(images, labels):
    num_classes = 12  # Number of Classes
    categories = np.unique(labels)
    keys = dict(labels["Label"])  # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
    rows = 3  # Defining number of rows=3
    cols = 4  # Defining number of columns=4
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))  # Defining the figure size to 10x8
    for i in range(cols):
        for j in range(rows):
            random_index = np.random.randint(
                0, len(labels)
            )  # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
            ax = fig.add_subplot(
                rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1
            )  # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
            ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])  # Plotting the image
            ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
    plt.show()

  • Shepherds Purse, Common wheat, Maize and Black Grass are having roughly above 200 iamges in each category
  • Loose Silky-bent are having around 600 images
  • Rest of them are between 400 to 500 images
  • To treat the class imbalance I will increase the weights of the minority classes and use it in my model

Resizing images¶

  • To address the computationally expensive issue while training on these larger images, I'm going to reduce image size from 128 to 64.
In [11]:
images_decreased = []
height = 64
width = 64
dimensions = (width, height)
for i in range(len(images)):
    images_decreased.append(
        cv2.resize(images[i], dimensions, interpolation=cv2.INTER_LINEAR)
    )

Making the data compatible by applying these three techniques.¶

  • Convert labels from names to one hot vectors
  • Normalizing the values
  • Treat the class imbalance by increasing the weights of the minority classes.
Adjusting weights for minority classes¶
In [17]:
from sklearn.utils import class_weight

labelList = labels.Label.unique()
class_weights = class_weight.compute_class_weight(
    class_weight="balanced", classes=np.array(labelList), y=y_train.values.reshape(-1)
)
class_weights = dict(zip(np.array(range(len(labelList))), class_weights))

Model Building - Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

  • Creating a CNN model sequentially by adding the layers one after another.

  • Clearing the previous model's history from the session even if a single model can run multiple times on the same data and fixing the seed again after clearing the backend.

  • Set the seed for random number generators in Numpy this helps to reproduce the same results every time when run the code.

In [25]:
# Intializing a sequential model1
model1 = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model1.add(
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3))
)

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding="same"))

model1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding="same"))

# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model1.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
model1.add(Dense(16, activation="relu"))
model1.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Adding the output layer with 12neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model1.add(Dense(12, activation="softmax"))

# using Adam optimizer and categorical_crossentropy as loss function with accuracy as metrics.
opt = Adam()

# Compile model1
model1.compile(optimizer=opt, loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])

# Generating the summary of the model1
model1.summary()

Plotting the Confusion Matrix¶

  • The Confusion matrix is defined as an inbuilt function in the TensorFlow module, using that for evaluating the classification model.
  • The Confusion matrix expects categorical data as input. However, y_test_encoded is an encoded value, whereas y_pred has probabilities. so it is better to retrieve the categorical values from the encoded values.
  • here argmax() function helps to obtain the maximum value over each category on both y_test_encoded and y_pred and obtain their respective classes.
In [31]:
# Obtaining the categorical values from y_test_encoded and y_pred
y_pred_arg = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
y_test_arg = np.argmax(y_test_encoded, axis=1)

# Plotting the Confusion Matrix using confusion matrix() function which is also predefined tensorflow module
confusion_matrix = tf.math.confusion_matrix(y_test_arg, y_pred_arg)
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True, linewidths=0.4, fmt="d", square=True, ax=ax)
plt.show()
Observations¶
  • The matrix shows that some of the classes are not predicted correctly.
  • In comparison to the rest, we can see that classes 0,3,6 and 7 are well classified.
  • Where as classes 1,2,5,7 8, 9, 10 and 11 are misclassified.

Model-2¶

  • The model-1 appears to overfit. I'm going to apply data augmentation and Batch Normalization techniques to check if model's performance has any improvement.
Data Augmentation¶

  • Why we need to applu Data Augmentation?: in most of the real-world case studies, it is challenging to acquire a large number of images and then train CNNs. To overcome this problem, one approach might consider is Data Augmentation. CNNs have the property of translational invariance, which means they can recognise an object even if its appearance shifts translationally in some way. Taking this attribute into account, can augment the images using the techniques listed

  • can augment the images using the techniques listed below -

  1. Horizontal Flip (should be set to True/False)
  2. Vertical Flip (should be set to True/False)
  3. Height Shift (should be between 0 and 1)
  4. Width Shift (should be between 0 and 1)
  5. Rotation (should be between 0 and 180)
  6. Shear (should be between 0 and 1)
  7. Zoom (should be between 0 and 1) etc.

# Intializing a sequential model3
model3 = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model3.add(
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3))
)

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding="same"))

model3.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding="same"))


# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model3.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons
model3.add(Dense(16, activation="relu"))
model3.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Adding the output layer with 10 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model3.add(Dense(12, activation="softmax"))


opt = Adam()
# Compile model3
model3.compile(optimizer=opt, loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])

# Generating the summary of the model3
model3.summary()

Transfer Learning using VGG16¶

  • For training VGG16, we will directly use the convolutional and pooling layers and freeze their weights i.e. no training will be done on them.
  • For classification, we will replace the existing fully-connected layers with FC layers created specifically for our problem.

sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True, linewidths=0.4, fmt="d", square=True, ax=ax)
plt.show()
Observations¶
  • The VggModel (model4) is not performed well compared to model 2. This could be due to dataset do not have correct images, learning module failed to apply proper filters.
  • Few classes 0,2, 3 and 6 are well classified.
  • But rest of them are misclassified
  • After analyzing all 4 models, I can conclude that Model-2 is performed well and which is the best model.
  • I'm going to use this model to predict and visualize some test images.

Conclusion¶

  • We can observe from the confusion matrix of all the models that our Model2 was the best model. It has overfit but compared to other models , the overfit is not that much.
  • When used model2 to predict images, Noted both actual and predicted images were matched.
  • The test accuracy of the model2 is ~60%.
  • Data Augmentation has also helped in improving the model2
  • Transfer learning model (Vgg) did not help much, I'm suspecting this is due the dataset.What the learning moduel had (convolution filters) might not done proper job with the dataset. This could be due to images were not included in the learning module.
  • If time is given and resources are not an issue, by applying few more dropout, batch normalization and other techniques, I could improve accuracy.
